  "prompt": "Does the ISS have a good WiFi connection?",
  "response": "The **International Space Station (ISS)** does have a form of internet connectivity, but it is not exactly the same as the WiFi connections we use on Earth. Here\u2019s how it works:\n\n1. **Connection Type**: The ISS uses a satellite-based communication system to connect to the ground. Data is transmitted via **Tracking and Data Relay Satellites (TDRS)**, which relay signals to ground stations on Earth.\n\n2. **Speed**: The connection speed varies depending on the system being used. The primary communication link provides speeds of **up to 600 megabits per second (Mbps)** for downlink (ISS to Earth) and around **25 Mbps** for uplink (Earth to ISS). However, these speeds are shared among all systems and crew members, so individual users may not experience these maximum speeds.\n\n3. **WiFi on Board**: Inside the ISS, there is a WiFi network that allows astronauts to use laptops, tablets, and other devices. This WiFi is connected to the satellite communication system, providing internet access. However, the connection is primarily used for mission-critical operations, scientific data transfer, and personal communication (e.g., emails or video calls).\n\n4. **Latency**: Due to the reliance on satellites and the distance between the ISS and Earth, there is some latency. This makes real-time activities like video streaming or online gaming less practical.\n\n5. **Astronaut Experience**: Astronauts can use the internet for personal communication, browsing, or even social media, but the connection is not as fast or reliable as on Earth. For example, streaming video or using high-bandwidth applications is often limited.\n\nIn summary, the ISS has a **functional and reliable connection** for mission-critical tasks and personal use, but it is not comparable to high-speed WiFi on Earth. It\u2019s more about staying connected than providing a seamless internet experience.",
